Traditional AI Infrastructure

Traditional AI infrastructure differs from the AI infrastructures used today, primarily in terms of scalability, processing power, and the ability to handle large-scale data and complex models. The following table illustrates several traditional AI infrastructure characteristics:

Traditional AI Infrastructure

Description

Hardware

The use of CPUs has transitioned to GPUs in newer traditional AI models.

Servers are typically found in on-premises deployment and generally require a high capital investment and maintenance costs.

Software

Traditional AI often uses proprietary software that is designed for only a particular task.

The algorithms are far simpler than the deep learning solutions in today’s modern AI environments.

All optimizations are traditionally done manually.

Data Management

The amount of data that is stored and processed is smaller compared to today’s requirements due to storage and processing limitations.

Often the handling of data is a manual process.

Traditional AI infrastructure can be broken down into three categories: compute, network, and storage. To achieve a successful AI-enabled application, administrators need to deploy the right hardware and software features, low latency lossless networks, and a storage configuration that supports AI application needs.

Compute

Specially designed servers, or nodes, are the foundation of traditional AI infrastructure. They are built on powerful servers with specialized processors called GPUs (Graphics Processing Units). It was discovered in recent years that GPUs are not only ideal for accelerating graphics cards and 3-D rendered spaces, but also for computing the algorithmic (vector) sums that are the result of deep learning processes.

These compute nodes typically house multiple GPUs (4, 8, or 16) each with an attendant high speed, 400 or 800G NIC, and an internal switch for data transfer between GPUs across a shared backplane. A compute node with eight GPUs typically supports eight 400G or 800G NICs, depending on the silicon used in the switching hardware.

Each GPU will connect to eight leaf switches, forcing a full mesh design pattern between GPUs and leaves, and forming a “cluster” or “rail” within the fabric. Clusters of clusters are also employed to achieve hyperscale fabrics that are sometimes made up of tens of thousands of GPUs. This quantity of GPUs is found in multi-billion parameter models such as OpenAI’s large language model, ChatGPT (175 billion), or for Tesla’s self-driving cars.

Network

Optics bandwidth is a critical factor for AI/ML workloads because it directly influences the speed, efficiency, and scalability of data transfer processes. AI models have varying traffic patterns that will affect the infrastructure design. For example, some learning cycles of traditional AI can take days or even weeks to complete with large datasets. When communication between the server clusters involved in learning cycles has high latency or packet drops, the process can take much longer to complete, or in some cases, fail.

While general-purpose data centers can perform well with a 20:1 oversubscription ratio (where more devices share the available bandwidth than the network can support simultaneously), AI training typically requires a 1:1 subscription ratio. However, a 4:1 ratio is common with some types of AI workloads. Higher bandwidth enables faster communication and processing, resulting in improved performance in AI/ML applications. 400G and 800G optics enhance the efficiency of interconnectivity between servers, switches, and storage, ensuring optimal performance of the overall infrastructure.

Storage

The efficiency of AI model training and inference is heavily dependent on the storage infrastructure. Traditional AI storage solutions must not only handle vast quantities of data but also provide high throughput and low latency to keep up with the demands of compute and network resources. The storage system impacts both the speed at which data can be accessed and the overall scalability of the AI infrastructure.

InfiniBand with Remote Direct Memory Access (RDMA) is a common choice for high-performance AI storage due to its ability to reduce CPU overhead and provide low-latency, high-throughput data transfer. RDMA enables direct memory access from the memory of one computer into that of another without involving either one's operating system. RDMA facilitates faster and more efficient data processing—critical for large-scale AI workloads.

However, depending on the specific requirements of the AI models and the nature of the data, some traditional AI data centers may opt for IP-based storage fabrics. These systems can offer greater flexibility and are often easier to integrate with existing data center infrastructure, though they may come with trade-offs in terms of performance compared to InfiniBand.

In addition to the choice of fabric, the type of storage media used is also crucial. For AI applications requiring rapid access to large datasets, SSDs (Solid-State Drives) are often preferred over traditional HDDs (Hard Disk Drives) due to their significantly faster read/write speeds. Also, high-performance NVMe (Non-Volatile Memory Express) drives are increasingly being used to further enhance data throughput and reduce latency.

The choice of storage architecture—whether it be centralized, distributed, or a hybrid approach—also plays a critical role. Distributed storage architectures, for example, are often favored in traditional AI infrastructure to ensure scalability and resilience, enabling data to be stored and accessed across multiple locations.
